  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "The standard story allows us to cash out two very intuitive thoughts: that practically rational agents act for reasons that are somehow their own; and that these agents are causally responsible for their actions.",
    "It does this by saying that when someone acts, her reasons for acting are what cause her to act.",
    "More precisely, it says that actions are events causally linked to an agent's psychological states, where the causally responsible states also represent these events as fulfilling some end or goal of the agent -or, at least, as liable to do so.",
    "In this way it vindicates \"the ancient -and common-sense -position that rationalisation is a species of causal explanation\" (Davidson, 2001a, p. 3).",
    "'Rationalisation' is Davidson's label for the kind of explanation that reveals what someone has done as an upshot of their motivating reasons and of their ability to be appropriately guided by these."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "In this way it vindicates \"the ancient -and common-sense -position that rationalisation is a species of causal explanation\" (Davidson, 2001a, p. 3)."
